emographic changes and the exponential growth and expansion of taiko particularly in Southern California. Through her participatory ethnographic work, she reveals a complicated story embedded in memories of Japanese American internment and legacies of imperialism, Asian American identity and politics, a desire to be seen and heard, and the intersection of culture and global capitalism. Exploring the materialities of the drums, costumes, and bodies that make sound, analyzing the relationship of these to capitalist multiculturalism, and investigating the gender politics of taiko, Louder and Faster considers both the promises and pitfalls of music and performance as an antiracist practice. The result is a vivid glimpse of an Asian American presence that is both loud and fragile.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAsian American musicians. 0aJapanese American musicians. 0aMusic. 0aSocial sciences (General). 0aTaiko (Drum ensemble)zUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh  aasian american presence.  aasian american taiko.  abodies.  acostumes.  acultural.  adrums.  agender politics of taiko.  ajapanese american internment.  alegacies of imperialism.  amusic and performance as antiracist practice.  aoriginated in japan.  astudy of asian american taiko.  ataiko growth in southern california.  athundering athletic drumming tradition.  avivid.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508